ðŸ“Œ 1. ls â€“ List Directory Contents

Description:
Shows all files and folders in the current directory.

Example:

ls


Output:

access.log  folder1  folder2  folder3

ðŸ“Œ 2. cd â€“ Change Directory

Description:
Used to move into another directory.

Example:

cd folder1

ðŸ“Œ 3. cd .. â€“ Go Back One Directory

Description:
Moves back to the parent directory.

Example:

cd ..

ðŸ“Œ 4. pwd â€“ Print Working Directory

Description:
Displays the full path of the current directory.

Example:

pwd


Output:

/home/tryhackme

ðŸ“Œ 5. find -name â€“ Find a File by Name

Description:
Searches for a file or folder by its exact name.

Example:

find -name passwords.txt


Output:

./folder1/passwords.txt

ðŸ“Œ 6. find -name "*.txt" â€“ Find All .txt Files

Description:
Finds all files ending with .txt using a wildcard.

Example:

find -name "*.txt"


Output:

./folder1/passwords.txt
./Documents/todo.txt

ðŸ“Œ 7. grep "THM" access.log â€“ Search Inside a File

Description:
Searches inside access.log for lines containing THM.

Example:

grep "THM" access.log


Output:

THM{GREP_ME}

âš™ï¸ Linux Operators
ðŸ“Œ 8. & â€“ Run Command in Background

Description:
Runs a command in the background so you can continue working.

Example:

cp bigfile.zip /backup/ &

ðŸ“Œ 9. && â€“ Run Next Command if First Succeeds

Description:
Runs multiple commands in one line.
Second command runs only if the first is successful.

Example:

mkdir test && cd test

ðŸ“Œ 10. > â€“ Output Redirect (Overwrite)

Description:
Redirects output to a file and overwrites existing content.

Example:

echo password123 > passwords

ðŸ“Œ 11. >> â€“ Output Redirect (Append)

Description:
Appends output to the end of a file without deleting existing content.

Example:

echo tryhackme >> passwords

